<span id="freeTextContainer11549468951633000869">I am just as pleased with this, the second installment of the Isaac trilogy, as I was with the first! It&apos;s refreshing to read a thick book where the main theme is religion. I love that the book is, in essence, non-denominational. I smiled when Jake realized he loved Amy&apos;s modesty in clothing; I wept when I finally discovered the details of Isaac and Lilly&apos;s backstory; I grinned when Amy&apos;s father was given a dose of humility; I ached for Mr. Allan and his collections. The woodcuts at the beginnin</span>
  <span id="freeText11549468951633000869" style="display:none">I am just as pleased with this, the second installment of the Isaac trilogy, as I was with the first! It's refreshing to read a thick book where the main theme is religion. I love that the book is, in essence, non-denominational. I smiled when Jake realized he loved Amy's modesty in clothing; I wept when I finally discovered the details of Isaac and Lilly's backstory; I grinned when Amy's father was given a dose of humility; I ached for Mr. Allan and his collections. The woodcuts at the beginning of each chapter were a beautiful touch, and the sprinkling of Quaker proverbs throughout left me feeling comforted and at peace. Honestly, I would love to live in Niederbipp! I'm excited to read the final book!</span>
